ngoList.detailsOfAchievement: Maharashtra Information Technology Support Center is registered under society act 1860. We have been working for the noble cause of youth empowerment. Since 2006 our major presence is in the state of Maharashtra. Our focus is on providing job specific skills to youth as per the local & global demand of the industries. We are associated with more than 8 multi faculty universities in the state of Maharashtra, this association is through the higher & technical ministries of the government of Maharashtra. Our motto is to provide value added skilled human resources. Along with developing entrepreneurial skills among the youth. We are working with government of India & government of Maharashtra to implement their various schemes & programmer related to skill development empowerment of youth. Our efforts & initiatives in this field will be ultimately useful for national development with national productivity. During this span of a decade we have provided services to more than 33 thousands youth in 8 universities covering are of 25 districts. We are efficiently implementing the schemes & programmmes with the help of network of more than 100 youth welfare centers. We are playing catalytic role in collaboration with more than thousands industries by providing them human resources & at the same time providing employment to the youth. Our activities & programmmes are multidimensional; presently we have focused on 8 sectors in the skill development programmer. With a balance view with gender sensitivity approach. We are empowering Self Help Group (SHG) of human, focusing on the sectors like IT, Apparel making & Bakery Product. We have well defined, useful future plans for the corporate world & the academic institutes to provide various special services for quality enhancement in the higher education & corporate management. Our target for the next 10 years is to train 1 lac youth including under graduate, graduate & post graduate at the same time we are going to provide special attention for youth.
